aremont]] and artwork by [[John Buscema]].\n\nMadripoor received an entry in the ''[[Official Handbook of the Marvel Universe|Official Handbook of the Marvel Universe Update '89]]'' #4.\n\nIt appeared in the fourth issue of ''[[Hawkeye (Clint Barton)|Hawkeye]] Vol. 4'' by Matt Fraction, as well as [[The Punisher War Zone]] #22 (December 1993) by [[Larry Hama]].\n\nMadripoor appears once again in the twenty-fourth issue of [[Uncanny X-Force]] by [[Rick Remender]]\n\nMadripoor appears in 2017 as a primary location in ''X-Men Blue'' by [[Cullen Bunn]].\n\n==Fictional island history==\nMadripoor is a fictional island apparently modeled on [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Boatz | first = Darrel L. | date = November 1988 | title = John Buscema | work = [[Comics Interview]] | issue = 62 | pages = 18\u201319 | publisher = [[Fictioneer Books]]}}</ref> They are both Southeast Asian island port nations with a single major city. Its capital and single large city is Madripoor, which is divided between '''Hightown''' and '''Lowtown'''. This serves to represent the extreme social inequality in Madripoor, described as \"a place for the very rich and the very poor\".\n\nMadripoor was once a haven for [[Piracy|pirate]]s,<ref>''Old Man Logan'' #34 (2018). Marvel Comics.</ref> and that tradition is somewhat continued today with its lawless quality. The principality does not allow other nations to [[extradition|extradite]] criminals. However, it is one of the business capitals of the [[Pacific Rim]], with its own [[World Trade Centers Association|Trade Center]].{{citation needed|date=August 2007}}\n\nOther locations of note in the Central Business District are the Bank of Hong Kong and the Bank of Malaysia, luxurious Sovereign Hotel, and the Prince's Palace, said to rival [[Palace of Versailles|Versailles]].<ref>''Wolverine'' #6 (April 1989). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nAn attempt was made to conquer the nation by [[China]]. General Lo Chien attempts an invasion using modern and mystical weaponry but is stopped by the ad-hoc 'Heroes for Hire' group.<ref>''Heroes for Hire'' #18-19 (Dec. 1998, Jan. 1999). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nThe nation was taken over by [[Hydra (comics)|HYDRA]] with [[Viper (Madame Hydra)|Madame Hydra]] as de facto ruler, using the nation to finance terrorist plots against the world. Side-effects of this are seen in ''Spider-Woman: Agent Of [[S.W.O.R.D. (comics)|S.W.O.R.D.]]''<ref>''Spider-Woman: Agent Of S.W.O.R.D.'' #1-5 (2009). Marvel Comics.</ref> With HYDRA's terrorist operations causing deaths in the thousands, [[Iron Man]] and [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]] took it upon themselves to overthrow the HYDRA regime and place the nation in the hands of [[Jessan Hoan|Tyger Tiger]], as she was the only person\u2014apart from the long-absent [[Wolverine (character)|Patch]]\u2014who the natives would follow in the event of a revolt. Stark wanted someone who would run Madripoor the right way without needing someone else to monitor them and ensure that the situation did not repeat itself.<ref>''Iron Man: Director of S.H.I.E.L.D.'' Annual #1 (November 2007). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nDespite this, the real power fell to Seraph, the owner and operator of the Princess Bar. Her death followed the death of Police Chief Tai. Criminal elements began fighting over Madripoor, forcing Tiger Tyger into hiding. Viper tried to make a return, with programmable murderous entities called [[Predator X (comics)|Predator X]].<ref>''Astonishing Tales'' #3 (2009). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nMadripoor is later controlled by Wolverine's son [[Daken]] after he managed to wrestle and manipulate power away from Tyger Tiger by acquiring control of various financial resources and key people. This results in several days of intense violence throughout the entire nation.<ref>''Dark Wolverine'' #5-7 (2011). Marvel Comics.</ref> Part of this chaos was the result of [[Malcolm Colcord]], who wanted free rein in Madripoor to for his super-soldier experiments. Colcord was stopped by Daken, Tyger, [[X-23]] and Gambit. After Daken's death, Tyger Tiger was once again the figurehead of Madripoor.\n\nA prominent Madripoor hotel was later used to hold an auction for a videotape of [[Hawkeye (Clint Barton)|Hawkeye]] committing an illegal assassination. Barton was captured while trying to retrieve the tape, but was rescued by [[Hawkeye (Kate Bishop)|Kate Bishop]], who had infiltrated the hotel by tying up and gagging [[Madame Masque]] and stealing her identity.<ref>''Hawkeye'' #4-5. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nIn the pages of ''[[Avengers World]]'', it is revealed that Madripoor rests on the head of a giant dragon that is as large as an island continent. The giant dragon was awakened by a ritual performed by [[Gorgon (Tomi Shishido)|Gorgon]] and the [[The Hand (comics)|Hand]].<ref name=\"Avengers World #1\">''Avengers World'' #3 (Feb. 2014)</ref> The beast decides to attack Shanghai, China.<ref>''Avengers World'' #13 (2014). Marvel Comics.</ref> It is beaten and returned in the following issue by Shang-Chi.<ref>''Avengers World'' #14 (2014). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nMystique tried to make Madripoor a mutant utopia; this involved flooding the island with 'Mutant Growth Hormone', a drug which grants powers.<ref>''All-New X-Men'' #37 (2012). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n[[Magneto (Marvel Comics)|Magneto]] and the [[All-New X-Men|time displaced X-Men]] use Madripoor's Hightown as the location for their headquarters in ''X-Men Blue'' where Magneto is secretly trying to find a way to send the time-displaced X-Men back to their original timeline under the guise of working alongside them.<ref>''X-Men Blue'' #1 (2017)</ref> At the same time, the time-displaced X-Men secretly train themselves in case Magneto returns to his villainous roots and tries to kill them.<ref>''X-Men Blue'' #2 (2017). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nTyger Tiger re-establishes herself as the pre-eminent power on the island. She is opposed by the criminal Kimura, who has gained control over most of the criminal elements. A failed assassination attempt on Tyger is stopped by the X-Men, Gambit and the young hero Gabby.<ref>''All-New Wolverine'' #16-17 (2017). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nDuring the \"[[Hunt for Wolverine]]\" storyline, Kitty Pryde led Domino, Jubilee, Psylocke, Rogue, and Storm to Madripoor to confront Magneto when he was suspected of stealing Wolverine's body. He agreed to tell them everything he knows at the King's Impresario Restaurant in Hightown. When it came to the meeting, it was revealed that Magneto is actually [[Mindblast]] in disguise as Kitty Pryde's group are attacked by Viper, [[Knockout (Marvel Comics)|Knockout]], [[Sapphire Styx]], and [[Whiplash (Marvel Comics)|Snake Whip]]. This trip also included investigating Madripoor's space launching facilities, which are available for anyone to rent.<ref>''Hunt for Wolverine: Mystery in Madripoor'' #1-4 Marvel Comics (2018). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nWolverine learns, through an adventure with the Black Cat, that the pre-teen criminal conspiracy called \"The Hellfire Club,\" has taken over the criminal underworld of Madripoor.<ref>''Black Cat'' #10 (2020). Marvel Comics.</ref> This group, sometimes referred to as Homines Verendi, has taken direct hostile action against the island nation [[Krakoa]].<ref>''Marauders'' #09-11 (2020). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nDuring the \"Iron Man 2020\" event, [[Albert (comics)|Albert]] arrived on Madripoor looking for Elsie-Dee. After meeting Tyger Tiger, Albert was directed to Donald Pierce's company Reavers Universal Robotics where he confronted Donald Pierce. After Albert subdues the Reavers, Donald states that he sold Elsie-Dee's head to yakuza boss Kimura, the arms to the Jade Dragon Triad, and the legs to the Vladivostok Mafia. After he gets the parts from them, Albert puts Elsie-Dee back together. In light of Albert's actions towards them, the Reavers, Kimura, the Jade Dragon Triad, and the Vladivostok Mafia to take action against Albert vowing that he will never make it out of Madripoor alive.<ref name=\"2020 iWolverine #1\">''2020 iWolverine'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nMadripoor is estimated to be {{convert|100|mi|km}} in diameter. Its coastline is pockmarked with [[Headlands and bays|deep water bays]] and [[inlet]]s. The center of the island is a large plateau with steep cliffs. As mentioned above, Madripoor rests on the head of a giant dragon that is as large as an island continent.<ref name=\"Avengers World #1\"/>\n\n===Points of interest===\nThe following are locations found in Madripoor:\n\n* '''Buccaneer Bay''' - This is where Madripoor corsairs ranged far and wide for their prey. It is also called Dagger Bay.\n* '''Hightown''' - A district of Madripoor for the rich and powerful. Hightown is one of the wealthiest places in the world. Its spectacular architecture and advanced technology make it truly a city of the 21st century.\n** '''Imperial Hotel''' - A hotel where Wolverine once rescued Lindsay McCabe.<ref>''Wolverine'' Vol. 2 #1. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n** '''King's Impresario Restaurant''' - A popular restaurant in Hightown.\n** '''Madripoor Police Force Headquarters''' - The headquarters of the Madripoor Police Force.\n** '''Reavers Universal Robotics''' - A factory owned by Donald Pierce where he has improved the production of his Reavers.<ref name=\"2020 iWolverine #1\"/>\n** '''Royal Palace''' - \n** '''Sovereign Hotel''' - It is claimed to be the expensive yet finest hotel in the whole world.\n** '''[[X-Mansion]]''' - A base of operations in Madripoor and a variation of the X-Mansion where Magneto and the time-displaced X-Men work on preserving [[Professor X]]'s dream by actively seeking out threats against it. It is also where Magneto is working on finding a way to send the time-displaced X-Men back to their original timeline.\n* '''Lowtown''' - The crime-impoverished district of Madripoor. Lowtown is a throwback to the lawlessness of a thousand years ago: a place of rampant crime and depravity where anything can be bought.\n** '''Brass Monkey Saloon''' - It is also called the Bronze Monkey and located on 332 Cyan Street.<ref>''Captain America'' #363. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n** '''Club Azimut''' - A nightclub that is a front for the Vladivostok Mafia.<ref name=\"2020 iWolverine #1\"/>\n** '''Dream Street''' - A street in Lowtown.<ref>''Wolverine'' Vol. 2 #32. Marvel Vomics.</ref>\n** '''Foxy Den Strip Bar''' - <ref>''Iron Man: Director of S.H.I.E.L.D. Annual'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n** '''Harbor Bar''' - Thunderbolt Ross once visited this bar before looking for recruits for his incarnation of the [[Thunderbolts (comics)|Thunderbolts]].<ref>''Thunderbolts'' Vol. 2 #2. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n** '''Jade Dragon Triad's Factory''' - A factory that is owned by the Jade Dragon Triad who use the slave labor their for their operations like making counterfeit Iron Man toys.<ref name=\"2020 iWolverine #1\"/>\n** '''Madame Joy's Brothel''' - A brothel that is owned by Madame Joy.\n** '''Princess Bar''' - A drinking establishment in Lowtown. It was run by a man named O'Donnell and his silent partner Wolverine (under the alias of \"Patch\"). The Princess Bar serves as an oasis of elegance and style. Frightened by Lowtown's dangerous reputation, tourists avoid the Princess Bar after dark. At night, the Princess Bar becomes a gathering place for local residents from both Hightown and Lowtown. The Princess Bar is also a fine restaurant with cabaret entertainment.<ref>\"Death Of Wolverine\" #2 (Sept. 2014)</ref> It is connected to a wide network of smuggling tunnels via the basement. Its second floor is off-limits to most.<ref>\"Wolverine Encyclopedia\" Vol. 1 #2 (Dec. 1996)</ref> <ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=cPboAAAACAAJ&dq=X-Men+Updated+Edition:+The+Ultimate+Guide&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQ45ns6JfZAhUHWK0KHbLfBRwQ6AEIKDAA X:Men The Ultimate Guide]</ref>\n** '''Wharfside''' - One of the worst spots in Lowtown.\n* '''Empty Quarter''' - A section of the city where one street does NOT consistently lead to the next. The only stable point is by the lighthouse. Attempted flight from the Empty Quarter leads straight into the [[Negative Zone]].<ref>''Wolverine'' #6 (May 2014). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n* '''Stinger''' - A [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]] safehouse and second generation secret base whose location is only known to [[Nick Fury]].\n\n==Known residents==\nNotable current and former residents of Madripoor include:\n\n* [[Warren Worthington III|Angel]] (past) - Currently living in Madripoor with Magneto\n* [[Archie Corrigan]] (deceased) - Owner of South Seas Skyways.\n* [[Beast (comics)|Beast]] (past) - Currently living in Madripoor with Magneto\n* [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Cyclops]] (past) - Currently living in Madripoor with Magneto\n* [[Dragoness (comics)|Dragoness]] - Former [[Mutant Liberation Front|MLF]] member and current resident of [[Utopia (comics)|Utopia]].\n* [[Harriers (comics)|Harriers]] - A team of mercenaries.<ref>''Wolverine'' #5 (Mar 1989). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n* [[Iceman (Marvel Comics)|Iceman]] (past) - Currently living in Madripoor with Magneto\n* [[Karma (comics)|Karma]] - Member of the [[New Mutants]] \n* Lindsay McCabe - Actress.\n* Magneto - Currently living in Madripoor with the time-displaced X-Men\n* [[Jean Grey|Marvel Girl]] (past) - Currently living in Madripoor with Magneto\n* Mr. X - Champion of Madripoor.\n* O'Donnell (deceased) - The co-owner of the Princess Bar.\n* Patch (alias of [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]]) - Co-owner of the Princess Bar.\n* [[Prince Baran]] - Former ruler. Murdered by General Coy.<ref name=\"Wolverine Vol2 #98 Feb 1996\">''Wolverine'' vol. 2 #98 (Feb 1996). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n* Roche (deceased) - A crime lord.\n* Rose Wu (deceased) - A friend of Patch.\n* [[Roughouse]] - Enforcer to General Coy and Viper.\n* [[Sabretooth (comics)|Sabretooth]] - He once lived in Madripoor in 1959.<ref name=\"New Avengers\">''New Avengers'' (vol. 2) #10 (May 2011). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n* [[Scorpion (Carmilla Black)|Scorpion]] - She was born in Madripoor.\n* [[Sapphire Styx]] - A psychic vampire.\n* Seraph (deceased) - Former lover and trainer of Wolverine.\n* [[Spider-Woman (Jessica Drew)|Jessica Drew]] - Private investigator.\n* Tai - Chief of the Madripoor Police Force and ally of Logan.\n* Tyger Tiger (alias of Jessan Hoan) - Former revolutionary and current head of state.\n* [[Viper (Madame Hydra)|Viper]] - Terrorist and recently deposed ruler of Madripoor.\n\n==Alternate versions==\nA future version of Madripoor was the site of a battle between the [[Guardians of the Galaxy (1969 team)|Guardians of the Galaxy]] and the criminal gang headed by \"Rancor.\"<ref>\"Guardians of the Galaxy\" #23 (April 1992). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n==In other media==\n===Television===\n* Madripoor is featured in ''[[Marvel Anime]]'':\n** In ''[[Marvel Anime|Marvel Anime: Wolverine]]'', [[Shingen Yashida]] uses this location for [[Mariko Yashida]] and Hideki Kurohagi's wedding with its location being the Dragon Palace. There is a direct route to Madripoor's Dragon Palace called Hell's Road which is filled with traps and hostile residents. Hideki's father Juo was the first to make it through alive.\n** In ''[[Marvel Anime|Marvel Anime: Blade]]'', [[Blade (comics)|Blade]] and Makoto head to Madripoor where [[Deacon Frost]] was sighted. They run into Wolverine who ends up helping them when the Viper Gang is producing silver bullets for the Existence.\n\n* Madripoor appears in ''[[Ultimate Spider-Man (TV series)|Ultimate Spider-Man]]''. In \"For Your Eye Only\", Madripoor is mentioned by [[Phil Coulson]] as the location where [[Spider-Man]]'s \"Spinning Arachni-Discs\" are manufactured at the time when Spider-Man was fighting the foot soldiers of the [[Zodiac (comics)|Zodiac]]. The majority of the episode \"Game Over\" is set in Madripoor where Spider-Man, [[Captain America]], and [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]] try to track down [[Arcade (Marvel Comics)|Arcade]] where they must prevent him from accessing the controls of some nuclear missiles and starting [[World War III]].\n\n* Madripoor will appear in [[Marvel Studios]]'s limited series ''[[The Falcon and the Winter Soldier]]''.<ref>https://movieweb.com/falcon-winter-soldier-x-men-villain-ogun/</ref>\n\n===Film===\nMadripoor appears in ''[[Avengers Confidential: Black Widow & Punisher]]''. In the film, Black Widow and the Punisher are sent to stop an illegal sale of weapons arranged by the Russians and directed by Alexi Shostakov.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.marvel.com/universe/Madripoor Madripoor] at Marvel.com\n* [https://marvel.fandom.com/wiki/Madripoor Madripoor] at Marvel Wiki\n* [https://comicvine.gamespot.com/madripoor/4020-42665/ Madripoor] at Comic Vine\n\n{{X-Men}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional Asian countries]]\n[[Category:Fictional principalities]]\n[[Category:X-Men]]\n[[Category:Fictional island countries]]"}]}}}}